the behavior describes the computation correctness, not config loading. Injecting a test config dict exercises the failure boundary without module wiring.","test_description":"Construct a freshness-rule config with at least two categories (e.g., user_profiles=300s, product_catalog=3600s) and call the TTL computation function for each category. Assert the returned TTL matches the configured value exactly. Also assert that an unknown category either raises a well-typed error or falls back to a documented default — not a silent wrong value.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears at the boundary between the memory-pressure monitor and the strategy-selector: the monitor must report high usage, the cache layer must read that signal, and the strategy object actually in use must change. No single function owns all three concerns. REAL-INFRA: Memory pressure here is an internal byte-counter metric (application-level), not an OS-level query, so a real subprocess or OS call is not required — an in-process fake that increments the usage counter past threshold suffices. REJECTION-GATE: System was considered (OS memory APIs), but the description says 'configured threshold,' implying the cache tracks its own byte budget internally; no OS instrumentation is needed to reproduce the switch failure.","test_description":"Wire together the memory-usage tracker, the threshold comparator, and the strategy selector. Fill the cache to just below the configured threshold and assert the active strategy is LRU. Add one more entry to push usage over the threshold and assert the active strategy switches to LFU. Then remove entries so usage falls below threshold and assert LRU is restored (if the design supports hysteresis). Use a real in-process instance of all three components; do not mock the usage tracker.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears across the write path and the invalidation mechanism: the application writes to PostgreSQL, the invalidation hook must fire, the affected row IDs must be mapped to cache keys, and those keys must be removed. This spans at least two modules and their handoff. REAL-INFRA: A local test PostgreSQL instance is needed because the key-to-row mapping query runs against the actual DB schema; a naive mock always returns the pre-programmed result and will hide failures in the SQL or ORM mapping. However, a local containerized Postgres is sufficient — no real production DB or network required. REJECTION-GATE: System was considered because the word 'PostgreSQL' implies a real DB, but 'real DB' in this context means a local test instance (standard Integration), not a remote or production endpoint. The failure mode does not require OS-level behavior, real HTTP, or real network latency.","test_description":"Spin up a local PostgreSQL instance (e.g., via pytest-postgresql or a Docker fixture). Pre-populate the cache with several entries keyed from rows across two different tables. Execute a write (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) that affects a known subset of rows. Assert that cache entries whose keys map to the affected rows are gone, and that entries for unaffected rows remain. Test both single-row and batch writes. Verify the invalidation is atomic with respect to the write (no window where stale data is readable).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.33,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure (wrong entry evicted) lives entirely inside the eviction data structure's ordering logic — a doubly-linked list + hashmap for LRU, a frequency-bucket structure for LFU. Both are self-contained algorithms with no module handoff. REAL-INFRA: No I/O required; the cache is in-memory. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered because eviction is triggered by the cache reaching capacity, which involves the cache facade calling into the eviction policy — but this call boundary is thin enough that instantiating the real eviction object under test (not a mock) covers it without needing multiple separately-deployed modules.","test_description":"For LRU: create a cache of capacity N, access entries in a known order, then insert one new entry to trigger eviction. Assert the least-recently-accessed entry was removed, not any other. For LFU: create a cache of capacity N, access entries with known access frequencies, then insert one new entry. Assert the least-frequently-accessed entry (with ties broken by recency as per spec) was removed. Test the boundary: cache at exactly N-1 entries (no eviction), then at N+1 (eviction fires). Use real eviction-policy objects, not mocks.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.87,"Integration":0.11,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9756,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9756},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"